  title: Record of the Hall of Reading
  author: Cho Wei
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Those who build great halls must first nurture timber—the strength-wood and catalpa—for decades upon decades, waiting until they tower toward the heavens and soar above the valleys, before they may be used as beams and pillars. Those who journey ten thousand li must first seek the finest horses, nourish them abundantly with hay and grain, prepare their saddles with care, only then can they reach the distant lands of Yan and Chu. Thus it is with the nation: to nurture worthy talents in advance differs not from these things. This is why the Hall of Reading was established.

    I humbly reflect that in our dynasty, successive sages have passed down their wisdom, and letters and refinement daily ascend. King Sejong, possessed of divine insight and keen sagacity surpassing a hundred kings, wrought with such mysterious craft as to move in harmony with heaven and earth. He recognized that "without scholars versed in the Way, the rites and institutions of the realm cannot be set aright." He gathered widely the finest scholars of our time and established the Jiphyeonjeon. There, morning and evening, they lectured upon the art of governance. Understanding that "to penetrate the profound mysteries of principle and to comprehend the vast flood of all writings requires dedication to specialized study," he sent forth three scholars from the Jiphyeonjeon, including Gwon Chae, granting them extended leave at mountain temples to read freely. In his final years, he sent forth six more, including Shin Sukju, allowing them leisure to immerse themselves fully in learning. King Munjong continued this noble tradition, devoted to scholarly refinement, and likewise granted leave to six scholars including Hong Eung. Thus the flourishing of talent reached its peak in a single age, and the beauty of their writings rivaled those of China itself.

    When our present sovereign ascended the throne, he first opened the Hall of Literary Pursuits, reviving the institutions of our forebears' Jiphyeonjeon. Daily he sits in the Hall of Constant Exhortation, focusing his brilliance upon the classics. He honors the Way of the Sage, cultivates talent beyond all measure. In the year of Byeongsin, he again followed ancestral precedent, granting leave to six scholars including Chae Shou. This spring, he granted leave to eight scholars including Kim Kam, that they might read at the Temple of Hidden Righteousness. The palace kitchens provided their sustenance, the royal cellars their beverages. Envoys were dispatched bearing gifts most generously. The sovereign then issued an edict to the State Council: "Seek a place beyond the city walls and establish a hall for the study of books." The Council reported that there stood a small hermitage at Yongsan, abandoned and fallen into disrepair, yet ideally situated—open, serene, and spacious for the work of preservation and contemplation. The sovereign approved this proposal, sent officials to oversee the work, and within two months it was complete. Though the structure contained but twenty chambers, each provided coolness in summer and warmth in winter. The hall was then named the Hall of Reading, and I was commanded to compose this record.

    I reflect upon these words from the *Book of Poetry*: "The gracious gentleman—does he not raise up worthy men?" The flourishing of talent depends solely upon whether those above cultivate it well. If nurtured properly, many worthy scholars will arise to serve the kingdom. If neglected, the state will lack worthy persons—with whom then shall we govern? Should one merely covet the reputation of nurturing talent while carelessly selecting unfit candidates, small-minded opportunists will slip in among them. Should one not take heed?

    In the three ancient dynasties, talent arose through the schools. The Zhou methods of cultivating scholars were most detailed and rigorous. The Han system of selecting the exceptional and the Tang method of ascending the Islet of Immortals both merely gained reputation in their time—hardly worthy of emulation. Our nation alone, having accumulated refinement over a hundred years, with methods of teaching and guidance and systems of encouragement and cultivation, truly stands as the mirror and reflection of the Zhou ways. Beyond the school and the Academy of Worthies exists yet another place to nurture talent, selected with great care and treated with utmost generosity. Compared to the *Poetry*'s words—"at each meal nothing remains, and thus the beginning is not carried on"—what difference is there?

    The *Book of Changes* states: "The sage nurtures the worthy and thus extends this nurture to all people." The commentaries say: "To nurture the worthy is to nurture all people." Though today's provision of halls and sustenance seems removed from the art of governance, and the Emperor's attention to this amid the manifold duties of state appears unnecessary—yet when in future times the empire is governed and the sovereign's Way is adorned, these men may well bring about that peace and extend grace to the common people, and their merit will reach far beyond measure. As the timbers and the noble steeds find their use in their season, so too does the Crown Prince's priority here surpass that of all previous ages. Should not those selected here strive to repay the sovereign's gracious cultivation?

    The Way of the sage lies inscribed in the classics. The profound depths of the *Canon*, the diverse accounts in the histories, the vast expanse of the hundred schools—all must be gathered and encompassed. One must wade through their streams yet distill their essence, observe their convergence and grasp their principles, reach toward breadth yet return to brevity. Only then can one advance deeply and find their origin. The Way of sage-kings and hegemons, the foundations of ritual and music, penalty and rule, the essentials of self-cultivation, ordering the family, governing the state, and bringing peace to all—all lie here. To apply these to affairs depends only upon diligent effort. As Dong Zhongshu said: "Through determined study, one's knowledge broadens and wisdom grows clear; through determined practice of the Way, virtue daily flourishes and achievement becomes great." This effect is plain to see.

    But if one merely gathers the dregs, making them material for memorization, weaving empty ornament into flowery language merely to dazzle the world and deceive the vulgar—this is not the sovereign's intention in nurturing scholars. Alas! The work of learning lies in transformation. If one reads a book today yet remains the same person, and reads another tomorrow yet remains unchanged still, what use is there, however great the effort? Confucius said: "To study without reflection is futile." He also told Zixia: "Strive to be a scholar of noble character, not a petty scholar of mere cleverness." Should we not earnestly heed this?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Hall of Reading (讀書堂) was established during the reign of King Seongjong to provide dedicated scholars with protected time and space for intensive study of the classics and philosophical texts.
  - key: ''
    value: The Jiphyeonjeon (集賢殿), or Hall of Worthies, was Korea's premier institution for literary and philosophical scholarship, comparable to imperial academies in China.
  - key: ''
    value: King Sejong (r. 1418-1450) is regarded as one of Korea's greatest monarchs, known for his patronage of learning and creation of the Korean alphabet, Hangul.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "gracious gentleman" (愷悌君子) from the *Book of Poetry* emphasizes how virtuous leadership cultivates worthy individuals in the realm.
  - key: ''
    value: Dong Zhongshu (董子) was a influential Han Dynasty Confucian thinker whose emphasis on diligent study through effort influenced Korean Neo-Confucian thought.
